{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gisèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["name of Frankish origin, from the Germanic word <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. It was a common practice in medieval Europe to leave children as pledges for an alliance, to be brought up at a foreign court, and the name may be derived as a byname from this practice. This was the name by which the wife of  Duke Rollo  of Normandy (  <i>c.</i>860– <i>c.</i>930 ) was known. On her account the name enjoyed considerable popularity in France from an early period. Use of the name in English-speaking countries is much more recent, and is due mainly to the ballet Giselle (first performed in  1841 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Gisella","meanings":["name of Frankish origin, from the Germanic word <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. It was a common practice in medieval Europe to leave children as pledges for an alliance, to be brought up at a foreign court, and the name may be derived as a byname from this practice. This was the name by which the wife of  Duke Rollo  of Normandy (  <i>c.</i>860– <i>c.</i>930 ) was known. On her account the name enjoyed considerable popularity in France from an early period. Use of the name in English-speaking countries is much more recent, and is due mainly to the ballet Giselle (first performed in  1841 )."]},{"name":"Gisele","meanings":["name of Frankish origin, from the Germanic word <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. It was a common practice in medieval Europe to leave children as pledges for an alliance, to be brought up at a foreign court, and the name may be derived as a byname from this practice. This was the name by which the wife of  Duke Rollo  of Normandy (  <i>c.</i>860– <i>c.</i>930 ) was known. On her account the name enjoyed considerable popularity in France from an early period. Use of the name in English-speaking countries is much more recent, and is due mainly to the ballet Giselle (first performed in  1841 )."]},{"name":"Gisela","meanings":["from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ or ‘scion’.  See  <b>Giselle</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gisèle de RANCHICOURT was born in 1166, in Rebreuve-Ranchicourt, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France, her father, Jacques de RANCHICOURT, was 31 and her mother, Louise de TINGRY, was 21. She had at least 1 son with Simon d'OLHAIN. She died in 1220, at the age of 54."},"et":{"1166–1220":"1166–1220","1148–1195":"1148–1195","1188–1240":"1188–1240","1135–1196":"1135–1196","1145–1191":"1145–1191","1148":"1148","1135":"1135","1145":"1145","1166":"1166","1188":"1188","1220":"1220","1196":"1196","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","1191":"1191","Fresnicourt-le-Dolmen, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Fresnicourt-le-Dolmen, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","Rebreuve-Ranchicourt, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, França":"Rebreuve-Ranchicourt, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1166–1220":"1166–1220","1148–1195":"1148–1195","1188–1240":"1188–1240","1135–1196":"1135–1196","1145–1191":"1145–1191","1148":"1148","1135":"1135","1145":"1145","1166":"1166","1188":"1188","1220":"1220","1196":"1196","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","1191":"1191","Fresnicourt-le-Dolmen, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Fresnicourt-le-Dolmen, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, R